        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down, Kent</placeName>
                    <date>Fe. 7<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. 1845.</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>You have my best wishes for your success in your present application. You are aware that I have never had an opportunity of hearing you lecture, &amp; therefore cannot speak of your qualifications in that line; but I have great pleasure in adding, that I have always been struck by your remarkable powers in acquiring scientific knowledge of varied kinds, &amp; by your extensive reading. I think it will be generally acknowledged, that a capacity of this nature, must be eminently serviceable in teaching a subject of so divesified a nature as Geology.—</p>
<p>Believe me dear Sir | Yours very faithfully | C. Darwin <lb resp="#mjhawkins"/> E. W. Brayley Esq<hi rend="superscript">e</hi></p> 
                </div>
            </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Brayley was applying for the professorship of geology at University College London. His application was not successful and the post went to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3922.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Andrew Crombie Ramsay</ref> in 1847, T. Joyce having taught geology in the interim. See <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_529.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Bellot 1929</ref>. This letter was published in a volume of testimonials for Brayley, see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2661.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Freeman 1977</ref>, pp. 63–4.</note>
        </div>        
            
